25_unit_circ_intro


  1. Question

    The unit circle below has a radius of length 1. The coordinates of special angles are shown.


    Determine \(\sin\left(\theta\right)\).


    1. \(-1\)
    2. \(\frac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}\)
    3. \(\frac{-\sqrt{2}}{2}\)
    4. \(\frac{-1}{2}\)
    5. \(0\)
    6. \(\frac{1}{2}\)
    7. \(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\)
    8. \(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\)
    9. \(1\)

    Solution

    Each point is \((\cos(\theta),\sin(\theta))\). So, the horizontal coordinate is the cosine of the angle and the vertical coordinate is the sine of the angle.

    In this case, \(\theta=\frac{7\pi}{6}\).


    \[\cos\left(\frac{7\pi}{6}\right) = \frac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}\] \[\sin\left(\frac{7\pi}{6}\right) = \frac{-1}{2}\]

    So,

    \[\sin\left(\frac{7\pi}{6}\right) = \frac{-1}{2}\]
